    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.796/754</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of the British Embassy</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barclay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Assistant Secretary of State</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">Ref: 56/176/44</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, [<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-25">undated</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Berle</hi>: In the temporary absence of Mr.
                    Wright, I send you herewith a copy of a telegram, sent to us by the Foreign
                    Office on behalf of Lord Beaverbrook. This telegram is in reply to the message
                    we sent to London, containing the amendments you had suggested to the answer
                    which Lord Beaverbrook proposed to make to the question in the House of Lords
                    regarding your recent conversations about civil aviation, a copy of which was
                    enclosed in Mr. Wright’s letter of April 19th to you.<note n="96"
                        xml:id="d360fn96">Not found in Department files.</note>
                </p>
                <p>We will, of course, be very glad to forward to Lord Beaverbrook any reply you may
                    wish to make to the question he puts in the last paragraph of the enclosed
                    message.</p>
                <p>Yours very sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>R. E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Barclay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">Telegram From Lord Beaverbrook for the Assistant Secretary
                            of State</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>) <hi rend="italic">Dated
                            April 24, 1944</hi>
                    </head>
                    <p>Many thanks for your telegram.</p>
                    <p>I accept all your amendments.</p>
                    <p>I will let you know when the statement is to be made. You will have seen that
                        the Prime Minister dealt with a number of questions on the Conference in the
                        House of Commons last week.</p>
                    <p>There is still great interest on the subject. What news have you of the
                        Russians? We await your discussions with them which may make clearer many
                        issues.</p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
